<font color="#FF0000">THE FRUITS OF ANGER+PREJUDICE</font><br>
<tt>Fri Apr 25  1:12:17 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz or Barry, if I may,<br>
     We had a squad of Vietnamese interpreters assigned to our intelligence company.  They ranged from good to indifferent as soldiers, but were generally decent sorts.  Their sergeant was a guy who took his duty seriously, and bore up rather well for somebody who hadn't been given a leave to see his wife in 3 years.  I wouldn't give you the lowest whale dung in the Marianas Trench for the district police chief, but I fondly remember the village chief I once worked with as a warm and hoonorable man, and wonder if he's alive and well, by some miracle.  Same for our shoeshine boy.  10,000 years of the same climate and diet and Chinese cultural influence, and we'd probably look and act more than a bit like the Vietnamese.<br>
   <br>
     If you ever come to Philly; check out old St. Joseph's Catholic Church.  It has no streetside entrances or windows. The main entrance faces an interior courtyard.  Seems many of the good Protestants of the mid-1700's didn't cotton to those Papist newcomers, and it was necessary to build the first Catholic church a bit like a fortress.<br><br>
     And then there was my Cousin Bill's wedding when I was 12.  His bride, Madeleine, was Italian.  Have never forgotten my grandmother and all the other Deutche Fraus sitting around a table talking about how &quot;nice&quot; Madeleine was; as if it was the most amazing thing on earth that an Italian could be &quot;nice&quot;.<br><br>
     Our country and its people have come a long way in getting rid of ethnic or racial stereotypes, but we have just as long a way to go yet.  My parents raised the 4 of us to have as little of their own prejudices as possible.  For that I am forever grateful.  Has personal experience strained my ability to look at any person as a human being first?  Yes, but I don't let myself forget what I believe is right or wrong, no matter how pissed or outraged I get.  Can not say &quot;I never met a man I didn't like&quot;; as Will Rogers did though.  If you really look close; there are plenty of persons in all groups who will act like jerks or worse.  When my 2nd son was mugged in 8th grade; it was an equal opportunity team, the brains was Black and the muscle was Portuguese.<br><br>
     If we all came out of Vietnam experience with a common &quot;mad-on&quot; for all Vietnamese; then that would be an evil legacy.  
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


